Centrosema acutifolium

    Authority   Benth.
      Family    Magnoliopsida:Rosidae:Fabales:Leguminosae
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 4409

   Notes
   DESCRIPTION: Trailing-twining herbaceous legume with slender pubescent
   stems, rooting at the nodes. Leaves trifoliolate, central leaflet 5-8.5
   cm long and 3-3.5 cm wide. Inflorescence an axillary raceme with up to
   24 flowers inserted by pairs along the rachis; peduncle up to 19 cm.
   Flower papilionate, petals light violet. Pod up to 20 cm long. GROWING
   PERIOD: Perennial. Cutting intervals of 70-100 days and a 10-15 cm
   cutting height are suggested. USE: Grazed pastures in mixture with a
   grass, as a legume -only protein bank and cut-and-carry. COMMON NAMES:
   Centrosema. FURTHER INF: It originates in tropical America in the
   Orinoco region between 4-6ºN. It has been introduced in several
   tropical countries, including South-East Asia, Australia and several
   countries in Latin America. It tolerates up to 5 dry months. Adapted to
   very acid, low- to medium-fertility, well drained, light textured
   soils. Tolerant of high levels of available Al and Mn. It is drought
   tolerant and adapted to a 3-5 months dry season. Warm season growth
   only. Average annual temperature in its native distribution is about
   26ºC. DM yields may be between 5-20 t/ha/year. Rainy season: 1-3 (-5)
   t/ha/12 weeks DM, dry season: <1 t/ha/12 weeks DM.

   Sources
   [10]Grassland Index
   Mannetje L 1992 pp 80-82 [RAIN, DRA, TEXT, PH, FER, LIG]
   Steven R and Staberg P 2005
   Tropical forages 2005

